"Li L., Keller G.","Variability in Late Cretaceous climate and deep waters: Evidence from stable isotopes",1999,"Marine Geology","161","2-4",,"171","190",,,10.1016/S0025-3227(99)00078-X,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-0032706714&partnerID=40&md5=b32e24e34989823dc7c8ec0e3f995d15","Department of Geosciences, Princeton University, Princeton, BC 08544, United States","Li, L., Department of Geosciences, Princeton University, Princeton, BC 08544, United States; Keller, G., Department of Geosciences, Princeton University, Princeton, BC 08544, United States","Strong climatic and temperature fluctuations mark the Late Campanian and Maastrichtian as indicated by stable isotope records from the equatorial Pacific (Site 463) and middle and high latitude South Atlantic (Sites 525, 689 and 690). The first major global cooling decreased intermediate water temperatures (IWT) by 5-6°C between 73-70 Ma. At the same time, sea surface temperature (SST) decreased by 4-5°C in middle and high latitudes. Intermediate waters (IW) temporarily warmed by 2°C in low and middle latitudes between 70-68.5 Ma. Global cooling resumed between 68.5-65.5 Ma when IWT decreased by 3-4°C and SST by 5°C in middle latitudes. About 450 ka before the Cretaceous-Tertiary boundary rapid global warming increased IWT and SST by 3-4°C, though SST in the tropics changed little. During the last 200 ka of the Maastrichtian, climate cooled rapidly with IWT and SST decreasing by 2-3°C. During the global cooling at 71-70 Ma and possibly at 67-65.5 Ma, the sources of cold intermediate waters in the equatorial Pacific, Indo-Pacific and South Atlantic were derived from the high latitude North Pacific. In contrast, during the global climate warming between 65.2-65.4 Ma, the middle latitude South Atlantic was closest to the source of IW production and implies that the low latitude Tethys played a major role in global climate change. Climate changes, sea-level fluctuations and associated restricted seaways appear to be the most likely mechanisms for the alternating sources of IW production.","Climate; Deep-water; Maastrichtian; Stable isotopes","Cretaceous; deep water; intermediate water mass; isotopic analysis; paleoceanography; paleoclimate",,,,,,"Abreu, V.S., Hardenbol, J., Haddad, G., Baum, G.R., Droxler, A.W., Vail, P.R., Sequence stratigraphy of the European basins (1998) Society of Economic Paleontologists and Mineralogists Spec. Publ., 60, pp. 75-80; Arthur, M.A., Dean, W.E., Schlanger, S.O., Variations in the global carbon cycle during the Cretaceous related to climate, volcanism, and changes in atmospheric CO2 (1985) The Carbon Cycle and Atmospheric CO2: Natural Variations Archean to Present, 32, pp. 504-529. , In: Sunquist, E.T., Broecker, W.S. (Eds.), Geophysical Monograph; Baker, P.A., Gieshes, J.M., Elderfield, H., Diagenesis of carbonates in deep-sea sediments-evidence from Sr/Ca ratios and interstitial dissolved Sr2+ data (1982) Journal of Sedimentology and Petrology, 52, pp. 71-82; Barrera, E., Global environmental changes preceding the Cretaceous-Tertiary boundary: Early-late Maastrichtian transition (1994) Geology, 22, pp. 877-880; Barrera, E., Huber, B.T., Evolution of Antarctic waters during the Maestrichian: Foraminifera oxygen and carbon isotope ratios, Leg 113 (1990) Proceeding of the Ocean Drilling Program, Scientific Results, 113, pp. 813-827. , In: Barker, P.F., Kennett, J.P., et al. (Eds.); Barrera, E., Huber, B.T., Savin, S.M., Webb, P.N., Antarctic marine temperatures: Late Campanian through Early Paleocene (1987) Paleoceanography, 2, pp. 21-47; Barrera, E., Savin, S.M., Thomas, E., Jones, C.E., Evidence for thermohaline-circulation reversals controlled by sea-level change in the latest Cretaceous (1997) Geology, 25, pp. 715-718; Barron, E.J., A warm equable Cretaceous: The nature of the problem (1983) Earth-Science Review, 19, pp. 305-338; Barron, E.J., Peterson, W.H., The Cenozoic ocean circulation based on ocean General Circulation Mo